title: Spatial Intersect Very Slow For Large Polygon and Large Index
description:
Hi all, I have indexed the entire geonames points (lat/long) with JTS enabled, and I am trying return all points (geonameids) within a certain polygon (e.g. Netherlands country polygon). This query takes 3 minutes to return only 10.000  points. I am using only solr intersect. no facets. no extra fitering.

Is there any configuration that could slow down such a query to less than 300 ms?

comments.content:
Wow; 3 minutes for 10k points.  Roughly how many vertices are on the polygon?

https://cwiki.apache.org/confluence/display/solr/Spatial+Search
There are some tricks to speed up polygonal search.  One is setting "autoIndex" on the field.  (no re-index required).  Just set that the true and leave it.  Then, fiddle with either distErr or distErrPct to get the precision you want and no more than you need.  Lastly, fiddle with prefixGridScanLevel  – set it to the grid level that the internal algorithm switches from recursive decomposition to scanning.  If you have a 20 level prefixTree, I recall it defaults to 4 off from the bottom, thus 16.
comments.author: David Smiley

comments.content: Oh and finally, before you do all this, do an optimize
comments.author: David Smiley

comments.content:
After the other things I mentioned, I suggest an experiment in which you use your largest POLYGON there instead of a MULTIPOLYGON, and see if that improves anything dramatically.

BTW I linked this issue to SOLR-10039 that will probably help this dramatically.  Although I think I'm going to punt on Polygon/Multipolygon support for a follow-up issue.

Some people who do polygonal search have use-cases that benefit from doing a reverse-geocoding lookup at index time such that your points will be indexed with information on what reference polygons matched.  I'm doing this on another project.  The down side is some inflexibility and longer indexing time... but up side is no complex/slow spatial queries at search time – it's basically a lookup.
comments.author: David Smiley

comments.content: Regarding your last sentence, how do I setup what you are proposing?
comments.author: samur araujo

comments.content: See my recent conference presentation which has some details: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=nzAH5QEl9hQ   and the code is https://github.com/cga-harvard/hhypermap-bop/tree/master/enrich including setup scripts.  Of course the details here are often particular to one's use-case/project but this should provide a good example to follow.  The point-in-polygon searches during data enrichment is working super-fast after all the optimizations, like a millisecond or so.
comments.author: David Smiley

comments.content:
How do I configure this strategy:
https://lucene.apache.org/core/6_2_1/spatial-extras/org/apache/lucene/spatial/composite/CompositeSpatialStrategy.html

This is the best configuration I got so far but still slow.
 <types>
    <fieldType name="string" class="solr.StrField"   />
    <fieldType name="srptgeom"
class="solr.SpatialRecursivePrefixTreeFieldType"
               autoIndex="true"
               distErrPct="0.015"
               validationRule="repairBuffer0"
               distanceUnits="kilometers"
               geo="true"
               maxLevels="8"

 spatialContextFactory="com.spatial4j.core.context.jts.JtsSpatialContextFactory"/>
 </types>

Notice, I index only lat/log and I am querying polygon with intersect.

I would appreciate if you could point out how to use compositestrategy, I
could not find a proper documentation.

comments.content:
In Solr, CompositeSpatialStrategy exists as solr.RptWithGeometrySpatialField.  I have no idea how well it would work with point data; it was designed with indexing non-point data in mind.   The following is a snippet of a JSON request to Solr's schema API liften from the hhypermap-bop project I linked to above:


  "add-field-type":{
    "name":"geom",
    "class":"solr.RptWithGeometrySpatialField",

    "spatialContextFactory":"JTS",
    "precisionModel":"floating_single",
    "validationRule":"repairBuffer0",
    "autoIndex":"true",

    "geo":true,
    "distanceUnits":"kilometers",
    "maxDistErr":0.005
    },



If you wish to continue with optimizing point queries, can you comment on how well prefixGridScanLevel tuning went?  Your configuration here is maxLevels=8 which translates to ~150km wide grid squares for your points; I doubt that's accurate enough for most spatial use-cases.
comments.author: David Smiley

comments.content:
Hi David, by default the schema.xml I sent you use geohash, right? In this case, I would expect that the maxLevels=8 has a 18km precsion at equator. How did you get to 150km?

Please check this spreadsheet for reference.
https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1HSsZAetPBlFgbGFbm0a4C8M587xpFC9Xkn3BIvDiJDs/edit#gid=0

Thanks for explanation on RPT. It is not for my use can.
comments.author: samur araujo

comments.content: Oh my mistake; I've been using quad trees a lot lately so I was thinking that.  Geohash will certainly be more accurate for same levels.  To avoid people having to actually compute this stuff, the "maxDistErr" allows you to articulate a distance instead of having to know what level that will translate to depending on the prefixTree you choose.
comments.author: David Smiley

comments.content:
Hi David, I notice that the quad  for polygon search is 3x faster than using geohash. 

The problem is that with its highest level (level = 29) it returns more results than geohash with level 16. 

So, it is 3x faster by less precise. 

Would make sense to allow a higher level in the quads? Or this lack of precision is due to other reason?
comments.author: samur araujo

comments.content: You're setting the levels explicitly but I don't recommend doing that – set it in terms of the largest distance you're willing to handle being the error (maxDistErr).  Both prefixTrees will then determine which level to use that satisfies that requirement.
comments.author: David Smiley

comments.content:
David, thank you for the last answer. It is clear now. 

I observed that for very large multipolygon (10MB) the query never finishes, but when I split the multipolygon into many polygons and issue a query for each polygon, it is really fast.

Does solr support  very large multipolygon as query parameter? Does it internally split the mulipolygon into polygons?

Could you clarify this point?
comments.author: samur araujo

comments.content:
I'm glad to be of help Samur.

Spatial4j is what parses the WKT string.  Assuming JTS is used as well, it constructs a JTS MultiPolygon.  However Spatial4j can natively handle collections of shapes; it's probably much faster.  Set useJtsMulti to false and I bet this will improve in performance a lot (defined here https://locationtech.github.io/spatial4j/apidocs/org/locationtech/spatial4j/context/jts/JtsSpatialContextFactory.html  ).
comments.author: David Smiley

comments.content:
David, I have 6 millions points in Netherlands and I trying to query them using the NL official polygon. 

I did all optimizations you suggested to retrieve them all (precisely).

I paginate the results using 100K as query limit together with nextCursorMark. I tried other limits but this one is the fastest.  I am using solr locally, 8 cores, SSD and 4G allocated to it.

It takes ~400ms for each page. Is it a good time for solr ? is it possible to do better than this without cluster?
comments.author: samur araujo

comments.content:
400ms for a page of 100K documents isn't bad; most of your time is I'm sure in retrieval; the query itself (i.e. time to return zero docs) is probably fast.  There are ways to retrieve data in bulk from docValues if you don't need a lot per document.  Sharding helps too.

I think further discussion should go to the mailing list.  It isn't apparent there are specific improvements to be done to Lucene/Solr code here.
comments.author: David Smiley
